 and confinement suffered by ordinary people of all colors in antebellum America and early Victorian England. Upstaging conventional stories and forms, giving direction and expression to the unruly attitudes of a burgeoning underclass, the plays in this anthology enact a vital force still felt in great fictions, movies, and musics of the Atlantic and in the jumping, speedy styles that join all these forms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansvLiterary collections. 0aAmerican literaturey19th century. 0aBlackface entertainersxHistory. 0aBlacks in literature. 0aMinstrel showsxHistory. 0aPopular literaturezUnited States. 0aRace in literature. 0aSocial classes in literature. 0aSocial classesvLiterary collections. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674274815zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674274815423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674274815/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK